<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="111">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="111">
This is a broadly Sino-Himalayan endemic species that seems locally abundant in the eastern Sino-Himalaya. 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1095-8312.1860.tb01045.x" author="Mitten, W" journalOrPublisher="Botany" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" pagination="89 - 128" refId="B49" refString="Mitten, W, 1860. Hepaticae Indiae Orientalis. Journal of the Proceedings of the Linnean Society. Botany 5 (18): 89 - 128, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1095-8312.1860.tb01045.x" title="Hepaticae Indiae Orientalis. Journal of the Proceedings of the Linnean Society." url="https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1095-8312.1860.tb01045.x" volume="5" year="1860">Mitten (1860)</bibRefCitation>
described 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mitt., J. Proc. Linn. Soc., Bot. 5 (18): 107. 1860" authorityYear="1861" class="Jungermanniopsida" family="Calypogeiaceae" genus="Calypogeia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Calypogeia lunata" order="Jungermanniales" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" phylum="Marchantiophyta" rank="species" species="lunata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">Calypogeia lunata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from Assam; later, 
<bibRefCitation author="Singh, AP" journalOrPublisher="Bryologie" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" refId="B63" refString="Singh, AP, Nath, V, 2007a. Hepaticae of Khasi and Jaintia Hills: Eastern Himalayas. Bishen Singh Madendra Pal Singh, Dehra Dun, 1-382." title="Hepaticae of Khasi and Jaintia Hills: Eastern Himalayas. Bishen Singh Madendra Pal Singh, Dehra Dun, 1 - 382." year="2007 a">Singh and Nath (2007a)</bibRefCitation>
recorded it from the East Khasi Hills and West Khasi Hills in India. Aside from India, the species was reported from eastern Nepal, Bhutan, Thailand and Yunnan Province in China (
<bibRefCitation author="Mizutani, M" journalOrPublisher="Botany" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" refId="B50" refString="Mizutani, M, 1979. Hepatics from eastern Nepal collected by Himalayan Expedition of Chiba University in 1977 46: 311-325." title="Hepatics from eastern Nepal collected by Himalayan Expedition of Chiba University in 1977 46: 311 - 325." year="1979">Mizutani 1979</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.5735/085.045.0501" author="Lai, M-J" journalOrPublisher="Annales Botanici Fennici" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" pagination="321 - 341" refId="B40" refString="Lai, M-J, Zhu, R-L, Chantanaorrapint, S, 2008. Liverworts and hornwort of Thailand: An updated checklist and bryofloristic accounts. Annales Botanici Fennici 45 (5): 321 - 341, DOI: https://doi.org/10.5735/085.045.0501" title="Liverworts and hornwort of Thailand: An updated checklist and bryofloristic accounts." url="https://doi.org/10.5735/085.045.0501" volume="45" year="2008">Lai et al. 2008</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Kitagawa, N" journalOrPublisher="Nova Hedwigia" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" pagination="163 - 170" refId="B39" refString="Kitagawa, N, 1988. Studies on the Hepaticae of Thailand V. The family Calypogeiaceae. Nova Hedwigia 90: 163 - 170" title="Studies on the Hepaticae of Thailand V. The family Calypogeiaceae." volume="90" year="1988">Kitagawa 1988</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Hattori, S" editor="Ohashi, H" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin, University Museum, University of Tokyo" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" pagination="206 - 242" refId="B32" refString="Hattori, S, 1975. Anthocerotae and Hepaticae. In: Ohashi, H, Ed., Flora of Eastern Himalaya, Third Report. Bulletin, University Museum, University of Tokyo 8: 206 - 242" title="Anthocerotae and Hepaticae." volume="8" volumeTitle="Flora of Eastern Himalaya, Third Report." year="1975">Hattori 1975</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Piippo, S" journalOrPublisher="The Journal of the Hattori Botanical Laboratory" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" pagination="1 - 192" refId="B55" refString="Piippo, S, 1990. Annotated catalogue of Chinese Hepaticae and Anthocerotae. The Journal of the Hattori Botanical Laboratory 68: 1 - 192" title="Annotated catalogue of Chinese Hepaticae and Anthocerotae." volume="68" year="1990">Piippo 1990</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Piippo, S" journalOrPublisher="The Journal of the Hattori Botanical Laboratory" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" pagination="135 - 158" refId="B57" refString="Piippo, S, He, XL, Koponen, T, Redfearn Jr, PJ, Li, J-X, 1998. Hepaticae from Yunnan, China, with a checklist of Yunnan Hepaticae and Anthocerotae. The Journal of the Hattori Botanical Laboratory 84: 135 - 158" title="Hepaticae from Yunnan, China, with a checklist of Yunnan Hepaticae and Anthocerotae." volume="84" year="1998">Piippo et al. 1998</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Long, DG" journalOrPublisher="The Journal of the Hattori Botanical Laboratory" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" pagination="381 - 440" refId="B42" refString="Long, DG, Grolle, R, 1990. Hepaticae of Bhutan II. The Journal of the Hattori Botanical Laboratory 68: 381 - 440" title="Hepaticae of Bhutan II." volume="68" year="1990">Long and Grolle 1990</bibRefCitation>
). The origin of the report of the species for Yunnan is unclear. 
<bibRefCitation author="Piippo, S" journalOrPublisher="The Journal of the Hattori Botanical Laboratory" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" pagination="1 - 192" refId="B55" refString="Piippo, S, 1990. Annotated catalogue of Chinese Hepaticae and Anthocerotae. The Journal of the Hattori Botanical Laboratory 68: 1 - 192" title="Annotated catalogue of Chinese Hepaticae and Anthocerotae." volume="68" year="1990">Piippo (1990)</bibRefCitation>
mentioned 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. lunata" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" rank="species" species="lunata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">C. lunata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
for Yunnan with reference to 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-92914-4_5" author="Grolle, R" journalOrPublisher="Bryological research" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" refId="B28" refString="Grolle, R, 1966. Die Lebermoose Nepals. Khumbu Himal, Ergebnisse des Forschungsunternehmens Nepal Himalaya. Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg, 262-298. https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-92914-4_5" title="Die Lebermoose Nepals. Khumbu Himal, Ergebnisse des Forschungsunternehmens Nepal Himalaya. Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg, 262 - 298." url="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-92914-4_5" year="1966">Grolle (1966)</bibRefCitation>
, who does not, however, provide label data for this species in Yunnan, although it is also indicated in the review of the general distribution.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="111">
The description based on the isotype is as follows: plants brownish to blackish brownish in the herbarium, translucent, glistening, 1.5-2.2 mm width; stem 120-220 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
wide, branching not seen; rhizoids sparse to common in brownish grayish, erect to obliquely spreading loose fascicles; leaves overlapping ~1/4-1/3 of next leaf basal part, slightly convex, with apices somewhat turned to ventral side, obliquely inserted and oriented, ventrally clearly decurrent to 1.0 of stem width or less, widely triangular-ovate, apex acute to obtuse (very rarely bilobed), 850-1200 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
770-1200 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
, margin entire to somewhat crispate; underleaves decurrent for (0.3-)0.5-1.0 of stem width, 1.5-3.5 as wide as stem, bisbifid or with each main lobe divided into three small lobes, or bisbifid with additional lateral tooth on each side; midleaf cells thin-walled, trigones vestigial, cuticle smooth, 30-38 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
20-33 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
(the cell measurements may be incorrect because of collapsed leaf cells).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="111">
The species is most morphologically similar to 
<taxonomicName class="Jungermanniopsida" family="Calypogeiaceae" genus="Calypogeia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Calypogeia goebelii" order="Jungermanniales" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" phylum="Marchantiophyta" rank="species" species="goebelii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">Calypogeia goebelii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Kitagawa, N" journalOrPublisher="Nova Hedwigia" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" pagination="163 - 170" refId="B39" refString="Kitagawa, N, 1988. Studies on the Hepaticae of Thailand V. The family Calypogeiaceae. Nova Hedwigia 90: 163 - 170" title="Studies on the Hepaticae of Thailand V. The family Calypogeiaceae." volume="90" year="1988">Kitagawa 1988</bibRefCitation>
), from which, however, it differs in underleaf width and shape, long decurrency of underleaves, rarely shortly bifid leaves (versus underleaves commonly less than 2 times as wide as stem and leaves deeply incised). In contrast to mainly Malesian-Papuasian 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. goebelii" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" rank="species" species="goebelii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">C. goebelii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. lunata" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" rank="species" species="lunata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">C. lunata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is characterized by an eastern Sino-Himalayan distribution, where 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. goebelii" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" rank="species" species="goebelii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">C. goebelii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can hardly be expected. We hypothesize that the reports of 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. goebelii" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" rank="species" species="goebelii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">C. goebelii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from Thailand (
<bibRefCitation author="Kitagawa, N" journalOrPublisher="Nova Hedwigia" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" pagination="163 - 170" refId="B39" refString="Kitagawa, N, 1988. Studies on the Hepaticae of Thailand V. The family Calypogeiaceae. Nova Hedwigia 90: 163 - 170" title="Studies on the Hepaticae of Thailand V. The family Calypogeiaceae." volume="90" year="1988">Kitagawa 1988</bibRefCitation>
and subsequent mentions based on this) represent the ill-developed modification (probably from dry habitats) of 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. lunata" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" rank="species" species="lunata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">C. lunata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. On the other hand, 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. lunata" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" rank="species" species="lunata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">C. lunata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
seems to be very closely morphologically related to 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. latissima" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" rank="species" species="latissima">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">C. latissima</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Philippines, see below), from which, however, it differs in its completely smooth cuticle and very rarely (as exclusion) bidentate leaves.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="111">
One more observation should be made on the type specimen identification. The specimen in JE marked as the possible type (JE-H2316 = JE04005930!) is actually not the type. The label means that the specimen was collected in &quot;Khasia, Churra&quot;, not in Upper Assam, as in the original description by 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1095-8312.1860.tb01045.x" author="Mitten, W" journalOrPublisher="Botany" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" pagination="89 - 128" refId="B49" refString="Mitten, W, 1860. Hepaticae Indiae Orientalis. Journal of the Proceedings of the Linnean Society. Botany 5 (18): 89 - 128, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1095-8312.1860.tb01045.x" title="Hepaticae Indiae Orientalis. Journal of the Proceedings of the Linnean Society." url="https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1095-8312.1860.tb01045.x" volume="5" year="1860">Mitten (1860)</bibRefCitation>
. The plants in the Jena 
<normalizedToken originalValue="‘type’">'type'</normalizedToken>
are different from the typical 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. lunata" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" rank="species" species="lunata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">C. lunata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and rather resemble 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. tosana" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" rank="species" species="tosana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">C. tosana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
or 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. goebelii" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" rank="species" species="goebelii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">C. goebelii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, although they differ from both in thickened leaf cell walls in dorsal half of leaves (especially in the external wall), V-shaped leaf sinus and 3-5 cells high undivided portion of underleaf. We speculate that the specimen may belong to an undescribed taxon, but we refrain from describing it here until fresh material suitable for DNA and oil body characteristics is obtained.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
